'''Connected Education''' - also known as Connect Ed - was a pioneering [[online education]] organization founded and administered by [[Paul Levinson]] and Tina Vozick.<ref name="Harasim">{{cite book | title=Learning Networks|author1=Linda Marie Harasim |author2=Starr Roxanne Hiltz |author3=Lucio Teles |author4=Murray Turoff | publisher=MIT Press | year=1995| isbn=0-262-08236-5 | pages=103‚Äì104}}</ref><ref name="T.H.E.">{{cite web|url=http://thejournal.com/Articles/1997/06/01/Technology-in-Education-and-the-Next-TwentyFive-Years.aspx|title=Technology in Education and the Next Twenty-Five Years -- THE Journal|last=Withrow|first=Frank|date=June 1, 1997|work=T.H.E. Journal|accessdate=21 January 2014}}</ref> Operating from 1985 to 1997, Connect Ed offered the [[Master of Arts|M.A.]] degrees in [[Media Studies]] (through [[The New School]] in [[New York City]])<ref name="Internet World" /> and [[Creative Writing]] (through the [[Bath Spa University|Bath College of Higher Education]] in [[England]]).<ref name="New Scientist" /> Connect Ed also worked with [[Polytechnic Institute of New York University|Polytechnic University]] in [[Brooklyn]] and [[Pacific Oaks College]] in [[Pasadena, California]].<ref name="New Scientist">{{cite news | url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg14820045.300-carry-on-learning-learning-cyberspace.html | title=Carry on learning | author=Ray Percival | publisher=New Scientist |date=1995-11-28 | accessdate=2008-08-25}}</ref>
Technical services were provided by the [[New Jersey Institute of Technology]] on their "Electronic Information Exchange System" (known as "EIES")<ref>{{cite book |title=The Virtual Classroom: Learning Without Limits Via Computer Networks|author=Starr Roxanne Hiltz|publisher=Ablex|year=1994|pages=57‚Äì58}}</ref> administered by [[Murray Turoff]] and [[Starr Roxanne Hiltz]], and by the [[Unison]] [[The Source (service)|Participate]] system. In an age before easy dissemination of images and sounds on the Web, Connect Ed classes were conducted entirely in text.<ref name="sheepskin">{{cite news| url=http://www.businessweek.com/archives/1994/b3394114.arc.htm| title=A sheepskin from Online U.| author=Paul Eng |publisher=''Business Week''|date=1994-10-17| accessdate=2008-08-24}}</ref> Features of the electronic campus included the "Connect Ed Cafe," for casual conversation; an online book ordering service; the "Connect Ed Library"; and an e-text publishing arm, "Connected Editions".<ref name="NYT">{{cite news|publisher=The New York Times (paid access)| title=LIFE STYLE:As Computer Bulletin Boards Grow, If It's Out There, It's Posted Here | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/04/02/style/life-style-as-computer-bulletin-boards-grow-if-it-s-out-there-it-s-posted-here.html?pagewanted=all| author=Michael Freitag| date=1989-04-02|accessdate=2008-08-25}}</ref><ref name="softserv">{{cite web|author=Softserv 4.03 |url=http://www.totse.com/en/ego/literary_genius/cat4-03.html |title=Catalog of paperless books available from Softserv |date=1991-06-05 |work=Softserv Catalog |accessdate=2008-08-25 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080702221749/http://www.totse.com/en/ego/literary_genius/cat4-03.html |archivedate=July 2, 2008 }}</ref><ref name="Netweaver"/><ref>{{cite web| url=http://mirrors.apple2.org.za/ftp.gno.org/doc/genie/a2pro/genielamp/aplp199303.txt | title=Digital Publishing News |last=Apple A2 Pro Roundtable|date=1993-03-01| publisher=GEnie Lamp A2Pro ~ A T/TalkNET OnLine Publication ~ Vol.1, Issue 02| accessdate=8 October 2010}}</ref> Courses included "Computer Conferencing for Business and Education," "Artificial Intelligence and Real Life," "Ethics in the Technological Age," "Science Fiction and Space-Age Mythology," "Popular Culture and the Media",<ref name="sheepskin"/> "Book Publishing for the 21st Century," "Technological Forecasting," "Philosophy and Technology," and "Technology and the Disabled".<ref name="Internet World">{{cite web|url=http://www.geteducated.com/articles/articles_old/iw.htm |title=geteducated.com |author=[[Vicky Phillips]] |publisher=Internet World |date=September 1996 |accessdate=2008-08-25 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080705095245/http://www.geteducated.com/articles/articles_old/iw.htm |archivedate=2008-07-05 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref><ref name="Netweaver">{{cite web | url=http://cgi.gjhost.com/~cgi/mt/netweaverarchive/000144.html | title=Connected Education, Inc. | author=Gail S. Thomas | work=Netweaver | publisher=Electronic Networking Association | date=1988-02-01 | accessdate=2008-08-25 | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080827214245/http://cgi.gjhost.com/~cgi/mt/netweaverarchive/000144.html | archivedate=2008-08-27 | df= }}</ref>
Students were enrolled in online classes from 40 states in the [[United States]] and 20 countries around the world.<ref name="New Scientist" /><ref name="NYT" /> Faculty and special lecturers included [[Michael A. Banks]], [[Gregory Benford]], William Benzon, [[Harlan Cleveland]], Ari Davidow, [[Sylvia Engdahl]], Keith Ferrell, [[David Gerrold]], Tom Hargadon, [[David G. Hays]], [[Michael R. Heim]], [[Nicholas Johnson]], [[Lionel Kearns]], [[Paul Levinson]], [[Brock N. Meeks]], [[Frank Schmalleger]], [[J. Neil Schulman]], [[Rusty Schweickart]], [[Donald B. Straus]], Gail S. Thomas, and [[Harvey Wheeler]] among others.
