{{about|the ceremonial MƒÅori dance|use in sports|Haka (sports)|other uses}}{{distinguish|Hakka}}
[[Image:MaoriWardanceKahuroa.jpg|thumb|upright=1.25|The haka is a traditional genre of [[MƒÅori culture|MƒÅori dance]]. This painting dates from {{circa|1845}}.]]
The '''haka''' ({{IPAc-en|Àà|h|…ëÀê|k|…ô}};<ref>{{cite web |title=haka noun |url=https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/haka |work=[[Oxford Advanced Learner's Dictionary]] |accessdate=25 June 2018 |language=en}}</ref> plural ''haka'', in both [[MƒÅori language|MƒÅori]] and [[English language|English]]) is a [[ceremonial dance]] or challenge in [[MƒÅori culture]].{{sfn|Jackson|Hokowhitu|2002|page=70}} It is a posture dance performed by a group, with vigorous movements and stamping of the feet with rhythmically shouted accompaniment. Although commonly associated with the traditional battle preparations of male [[warrior]]s, haka have been performed by both men and women,<ref name="haka.co.nz">[http://www.haka.co.nz/haka.php ''Haka'' is also the plural form in MƒÅori] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720050544/http://www.haka.co.nz/haka.php/ |date=2011-07-20 }}</ref> and several varieties of the dance fulfil social functions within MƒÅori culture.<ref>{{cite web|title=Haka, Maori dance|url=https://www.britannica.com/art/haka|work=[[Encyclop√¶dia Britannica]] |accessdate=26 April 2017}}</ref>{{sfn|Simon|2015}} Haka are performed to [[p≈çwhiri|welcome distinguished guests]], or to acknowledge great achievements, occasions or funerals.

''[[Kapa haka]]'' (performing arts, {{literally|line dance}}) groups are very common in schools.<ref>{{cite web |title=Kapa haka in mainstream schools ‚Äì Affirming MƒÅori students as MƒÅori {{!}} SchoolNews ‚Äì New Zealand |url=https://www.schoolnews.co.nz/2017/11/kapa-haka-in-mainstream-schools-affirming-maori-students-as-maori/ |website=www.schoolnews.co.nz |accessdate=25 June 2018 |language=en-NZ}}</ref> The main MƒÅori performing arts competition, [[Te Matatini]], takes place every two years.{{sfn|DANZ Quarterly|page=6}}

New Zealand sports teams' practice of performing a haka before their international matches has made the haka more widely known around the world. This tradition began with the [[1888‚Äì89 New Zealand Native football team]] tour and has been carried on by the [[New Zealand national rugby union team|New Zealand rugby union team]] ("All Blacks") since 1905.{{sfn|Hunt|2015}} However, this is considered by some MƒÅori to be a form of [[cultural appropriation]].{{sfn|Simon|2015|page=88}}{{sfn|Hokowhitu|2014|page=273}}

==Etymology==
{{See also|Kapa haka}}
{{Wiktionary|haka}}
The group of people performing a haka is referred to as a ''kapa haka'' (''kapa'' meaning ''row'' or ''rank''). The MƒÅori word ''haka'' has cognates in other [[Polynesian languages]], for example: Tongan ''haka'', 'hand action while singing'; Samoan ''sa{{okina}}a'', Tokelau ''haka'', Rarotongan ''{{okina}}aka'', Hawaiian ''ha{{okina}}a'', Marquesan ''haka'', all meaning 'dance'; Mangarevan ''{{okina}}aka'', 'to dance in traditional fashion; dance accompanied by chant, usually of a warlike nature'. In some languages, the meaning is divergent, for example in Tikopia ''saka'' means to 'perform rites in traditional ritual system'. The form reconstructed for Proto-Polynesian is ''*saka'', deriving ultimately from Proto-Oceanic ''*sa≈ãka(g)''.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}

==History and practice==
[[File:New Zealand Maori Culture 001 (5396249586).jpg|thumb|upright|When performed by men,<ref>{{cite web |title=Haka ‚Äì Ka Mate |url=http://www.themaori.com/maori-haka |website=www.themaori.com |accessdate=25 June 2018}}</ref> the haka features protruding of the tongue.]] 
===Origins===

According to KƒÅretu, the haka has been "erroneously defined by generations of uninformed as 'war dances'",{{sfn|KƒÅretu|1993b|page=37}} whereas [[MƒÅori mythology]] places haka as the dance "about the celebration of life".{{sfn|Simon|2013}} According to its creation story, the sun god, [[Tama-nui-te-rƒÅ]], had two wives, the Summer Maid, [[Hine-raumati]], and the Winter Maid, [[Hine-takurua]]. Haka originated in the coming of Hine-raumati, whose presence on still, hot days was revealed in a quivering appearance in the air. This was the haka of [[TƒÅne-rore]], the son of Hine-raumati and Tama-nui-te-rƒÅ.{{sfn|McLintock|1966}}{{sfn|Simon|2015|page=87}} Hyland comments that "[t]he haka is (and also represents) a natural phenomena; on hot summer days, the 'shimmering' atmospheric distortion of air emanating from the ground is personified as 'Te Haka a TƒÅnerore'".{{sfn|Hyland|2015|page=69}}

Jackson and Hokowhitu state, "haka is the generic name for all types of dance or ceremonial performance that involve movement."{{sfn|Jackson|Hokowhitu|2002|page=70}} The various types of haka include ''whakat≈´ waewae'', ''t≈´t≈´ ngƒÅrahu'' and ''peruperu''.{{sfn|McLintock|1966}} The ''t≈´t≈´ ngƒÅrahu'' involves jumping from side to side, while in the ''whakat≈´ waewae'' no jumping occurs. Another kind of haka performed without weapons is the ''ngeri'', the purpose of which was to motivate a warrior psychologically. The movements are very free, and each performer is expected to be expressive of their feelings. ''Manawa wera'' haka were generally associated with funerals or other occasions involving death. Like the ''ngeri'' they were performed without weapons, and there was little or no choreographed movement.{{sfn|McLintock|1966}}

War haka (''{{lang|mi|peruperu}}'') were originally performed by warriors before a battle, proclaiming their strength and prowess in order to intimidate the opposition.{{sfn|Simon|2015|page=88}}  Various actions are employed in the course of a performance, including [[facial expression|facial contortions]] such as showing the whites of the eyes (''{{lang|mi|p≈´kana}}''), and poking out the tongue (''{{lang|mi|whetero}}'', performed by men only<ref name="haka.co.nz"/>), and a wide variety of vigorous body actions such as slapping the hands against the body and stomping of the feet. As well as [[chant]]ed words, a variety of cries and grunts are used. Haka may be understood as a kind of [[symphony]] in which the different parts of the body represent many instruments. The hands, arms, legs, feet, voice, eyes, tongue and the body as a whole combine to express courage, annoyance, joy or other feelings relevant to the purpose of the occasion.{{sfn|McLintock|1966}}

===18th and 19th centuries===
[[File:MaoriWardance.jpg|thumb|upright=1.25|19th-century illustration of a haka, {{circa|1890}}]]
The earliest Europeans to witness the haka were invariably struck by its vigour and ferocity.{{sfn|Smith|2014a}} [[Joseph Banks]], who accompanied [[James Cook]] on his first voyage to New Zealand in 1769, later recorded, "The War Song and dance consists of Various contortions of the limbs during which the tongue is frequently thrust out incredibly far and the orbits of the eyes enlargd so much that a circle of white is distinctly seen round the Iris: in short nothing is omittd which can render a human shape frightful and deformd, which I suppose they think terrible."{{sfn|KƒÅretu|1993a|page=22}}

From their arrival in the early 19th century, Christian [[missionaries]] strove unsuccessfully to eradicate the haka, along with other forms of MƒÅori culture that they saw as conflicting with Christian beliefs and practice. [[Henry Williams (missionary)|Henry Williams]], the leader of the [[Church Missionary Society]] mission in New Zealand, aimed to replace the haka and traditional MƒÅori chants (''waiata'') with [[hymn]]s. Missionaries also encouraged European harmonic singing as part of the process of conversion.{{sfn|Smith|2014a}}

The use of the haka in welcoming ceremonies for members of [[British royal family]] helped to improve its standing among Europeans. [[Alfred, Duke of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha|Prince Alfred]], the [[Duke of Edinburgh]], was the first royal to visit New Zealand, in 1869.<ref>{{cite web |title=New Zealand's first royal visit |url=https://nzhistory.govt.nz/page/new-zealands-first-royal-visit |website=nzhistory.govt.nz |publisher=[[Ministry for Culture and Heritage]] |date=9 December 2016 |accessdate=25 June 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Upon the Duke's arrival at the wharf in [[Wellington]], he was greeted by a vigorous haka. The ''Wellington Independent'' reported, "The excitement of the Maoris becomes uncontrollable. They gesticulate, they dance, they throw their weapons wildly in the air, while they yell like fiends let loose. But all this fierce yelling is of the most friendly character. They are bidding the Duke welcome."<ref>[http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=WI18690413.2.11.1 13 April 1869], ''Wellington Independent'', p. 3. Retrieved on 25 June 2018.</ref>

===Modern haka===
[[File:Haka for Lord Ranfurly 1904.jpg|thumb|A group of men and women perform a haka for Governor [[Lord Ranfurly]] at [[Ruatoki]], Bay of Plenty, 1904]]
[[File:E 003261 E Maoris in North Africa July 1941.jpg|thumb|right|[[MƒÅori Battalion]] haka in Egypt, 1941|alt=A squad of men kneel in the desert sand while performing a war dance]]
In modern times, various haka have been composed to be performed by women and even children.<ref name="haka.co.nz"/> Haka are performed for various reasons: for welcoming distinguished guests, or to acknowledge great achievements, occasions or funerals. The [[1888‚Äì89 New Zealand Native football team]] began a tradition by performing the haka during an international tour.{{sfn|Ryan|1993|p=46}} The common use of haka by the national rugby union team ("All Blacks"; since 1905{{sfn|Hunt|2015}}) has made one type of haka familiar.<ref>{{cite web |title=History of the All Black haka |url=https://media.newzealand.com/en/story-ideas/history-of-the-all-black-haka/ |publisher=[[Tourism New Zealand]] |accessdate=25 June 2018}}</ref>

The haka has been a contested source of [[cultural appropriation]]. The 1979 annual "haka party" parade at the [[University of Auckland]] ‚Äì in which engineering students persisted in parodying the haka by painting male genitals on their body and performing with sexually obscene gestures ‚Äì was disrupted by a collection of MƒÅori and Pacific Island students (''He Taua'', or The War Party) headed by [[NgƒÅ Tamatoa]], a prominent MƒÅori activist group. The protesters included [[Hone Harawira]], later a [[Member of Parliament]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Yvonne |last=Tahana |url= http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10569951 |title=Haka brawl rivals unite to remember |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]|date=2 May 2009 |accessdate=1 November 2018}}</ref> Several of the engineering students were assaulted, and members of ''He Taua'' were arrested.{{sfn|Walker|2004|page=220‚Äì7}} Their court case in Auckland sparked anti-racism protests outside the courthouse. 

The choreographed dance and chant popularised around the world by the All Blacks derives from "[[Ka Mate]]",<ref name=teara/> a brief haka previously intended for extemporaneous, non-synchronized performance, whose composition is attributed to [[Te Rauparaha]] (1760s‚Äì1849), a war leader of the [[NgƒÅti Toa]] tribe.{{sfn|Jackson|Hokowhitu|2002|page=129}} The "Ka Mate" haka is classified as a ''haka taparahi'' ‚Äì a ceremonial haka. "Ka Mate" is about the cunning ruse Te Rauparaha used to outwit his enemies, and may be interpreted as "a celebration of the triumph of life over death".<ref name=teara>{{cite web|title=Chant composed by Te Rauparaha|url=https://teara.govt.nz/en/music/3918/chant-composed-by-te-rauparaha|website=teara.govt.nz|accessdate=4 November 2017|language=en}}</ref> Concerns were expressed that the authorship and significance of this haka to the NgƒÅti Toa were being lost and that it had "become the most performed, the most maligned, the most abused of all haka",{{sfn|KƒÅretu|1994b|page=68}} and was now "the most globally recognised form of cultural appropriation".{{sfn|Hokowhitu|2014|page=273}} Specific legal challenges regarding the rights of the NgƒÅti Toa to be acknowledged as the authors and owners of "Ka Mate" were eventually settled in agreements between NgƒÅti Toa and the [[New Zealand Government]] and [[New Zealand Rugby Union]], as published in 2009.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/asia-pacific/7882775.stm | work=BBC News | title=New Zealand Maori win haka fight | date=11 February 2009}}</ref><ref>[https://www.govt.nz/treaty-settlement-documents/ngati-toa-rangatira/ NgƒÅti Toa Rangatira Letter of Agreement] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100521222630/http://nz01.terabyte.co.nz/ots/LiveArticle.asp?ArtID=1234231829 |date=21 May 2010 }}</ref>

==Cultural impact==
{{Main|Haka in popular culture}}
[[File:Maori dancers.jpg|thumb|A performance by the Kahurangi MƒÅori Dance group, United States.]]

In the 21st century, ''kapa haka'' is offered as a subject in universities, including the study of haka, and is practised in schools and military institutions.{{sfn|Smith|2014b}} In addition to the national [[Te Matatini]] competition,{{sfn|DANZ Quarterly|page=6}} local and regional competitions attract dozens of teams and thousands of spectators.{{sfn|Smith|2014b}}

The All Blacks' use of the haka has become the most widely known, but several other New Zealand [[haka (sports)|sports teams now perform the haka]] before commencing a game. These include the [[New Zealand national rugby league team|national rugby league team]] ("the Kiwis"),<ref>{{cite news |last1=Burgess |first1=Michael |title=Rugby League: Kiwis perform haka for Liverpool football players |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=12151955 |accessdate=17 November 2018 |work=The New Zealand Herald |date=31 October 2018}}</ref> and the [[New Zealand men's national basketball team|men's national basketball team]] ("Tall Blacks").<ref>{{cite news |title=New Zealand haka war dance bewilders USA basketball team |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/video/2014/sep/03/new-zealand-basketball-team-perform-haka-team-usa |accessdate=17 November 2018 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=4 September 2014}}</ref>

In the lead up to the [[Rugby World Cup]] in 2011, [[flashmob]] haka became a popular way of expressing support for the All Blacks. Some MƒÅori leaders thought it was "inappropriate" and a "bastardisation" of haka,<ref>{{cite news| url= http://www.3news.co.nz/Maori-leaders-at-odds-over-flash-mob-haka/tabid/1534/articleID/226469/Default.aspx|work=3 News NZ | title= Maori leaders at odds over flash mob haka| date=20 September 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111227003042/http://www.3news.co.nz/Maori-leaders-at-odds-over-flash-mob-haka/tabid/1534/articleID/226469/Default.aspx|archivedate=27 December 2011}}</ref> despite its popularity. Sizeable flashmob haka were performed in Wellington<ref>{{cite news| url= http://www.3news.co.nz/Wellington-haka-attracts-hundreds/tabid/423/articleID/225039/Default.aspx|work=3 News NZ | title= Wellington haka attracts hundreds| date=8 September 2011}}</ref> and Auckland,<ref>{{cite news| url= http://www.3news.co.nz/Flash-mob-haka-on-Aucklands-Queen-Street-ahead-of-RWC-opener-All-Blacks-vs-Tonga/tabid/317/articleID/225146/Default.aspx|work=3 News NZ | title= Flash mob haka on Auckland's Queen Street ahead of RWC opener All Blacks vs Tonga| date=9 September 2011}}</ref> as well as London, which has a large New Zealander immigrant community.<ref>{{cite news| url= http://www.3news.co.nz/Flashmob-haka-takes-over-Trafalgar-Square/tabid/417/articleID/277172/Default.aspx|work=3 News NZ | title= Flashmob haka takes over Trafalgar Square| date=19 November 2011}}</ref>

In November 2012, a MƒÅori kapa haka group from [[Rotorua]] performed a version of the "[[Gangnam Style]]" dance mixed with a traditional haka in [[Seoul]], celebrating 50 years of diplomatic relations between South Korea and New Zealand.<ref>{{cite news| url= http://www.3news.co.nz/Maori-take-on-Gangnam-Style-in-Korea/tabid/418/articleID/278704/Default.aspx |work=[[3 News]] | title= Maori take on Gangnam Style in Korea| date=30 November 2012}}</ref>

On 7 December 2014, at the [[2014 Roller Derby World Cup]] in [[Dallas]], [[Texas]], [[Aotearoa Roller Derby|Team New Zealand]] performed a haka on roller skates to the [[Team Australia (roller derby)|Australian Roller Derby team]] before their bout in the quarter finals.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.facebook.com/video.php?v=953038331390867&pnref=story |work=Blood and Thunder World Cup Official Facebook | title= Team New Zealand vs Team Australia Haka | date=7 December 2014}}</ref> Team New Zealand performed a haka before their debut game against [[USA Roller Derby|Team USA]] at the [[2011 Roller Derby World Cup]], on 1 December 2011; however, it was unexpected and the arena music was still playing. It has since become an expected tradition.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fGSrnpuLnNg |work=Blood and Thunder World Cup Official Youtube | title= Team New Zealand Haka| date=1 December 2011}}</ref>

A number of [[Haka performed by non-New Zealand sports teams|American football teams perform the haka]] as a pregame ritual. This appears to have begun at [[Kahuku High & Intermediate School|Kahuku High School]] where  both the student body and local community includes many Polynesian Hawaiians, MƒÅori, Samoans, Tahitians, and Tongans. The [[University of Hawaii at Manoa|University of Hawaii]] [[Hawaii Rainbow Warriors football|Rainbow Warriors football team]] also adopted the haka as a pregame ritual [[2006 Hawaii Warriors football team|during the 2006 season]],<ref>{{cite web|title=2006 Hawaii Bowl UH over ASU ‚Äì UH Haka|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7qdGX-0NWIY|website=YouTube|accessdate=6 February 2016}}</ref> and the practice has spread to a number of other teams; however, this has been criticised as inappropriate and disrespectful.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/rugby-union/new-zealanders-outraged-over-awkward-haka-performed-by-arizona-wildcats-college-football-team-20151001-gjypbn.html|title=New Zealanders outraged over awkward haka performed by Arizona Wildcats college football team|last=Sygall|first=David|date=2015-10-01|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2018-10-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=11520336|title=Mixed reaction to an American haka|last=Carpenter|first=Cam|date=2015-09-28|work=The New Zealand Herald|access-date=2018-10-11|language=en-NZ|issn=1170-0777}}</ref>

