[[File:Product Made in Bangladesh.JPG|thumb|Ready-made garments made in Bangladesh]] '''Ready-made garments''' are [[mass production|mass-produced]] finished [[textile]] products of the [[clothing industry]]. They are not custom [[tailoring|tailored]] according to measurements, but rather generalized according to [[anthropometric]] studies. They are made from many different [[fabrics]] and [[yarns]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tis-gdv.de/tis_e/ware/textil/konfektion/konfektion.htm|title=Ready-made garments|website=www.tis-gdv.de|access-date=5 May 2016}}</ref> Their characteristics depend on the fibers used in their manufacture.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blogs.worldbank.org/endpovertyinsouthasia/important-role-ready-made-garments-bangladesh%27s-export-earnings|title=The important role of ready made garments to Bangladesh‚Äôs export earnings|website=worldbank.org|publisher=[[World Bank]]|author=Abul Basher|date=26 June 2009|access-date=18 January 2017}}</ref> Ready-made garments are divided into the following types: outer clothing, which includes workwear and uniforms, leisure wear, and sportswear (e.g., suits, pants, dresses, ladies' suits, [[blouse|blouses]], [[blazer]]s, jackets, [[Cardigan (sweater)|cardigans]], [[pullovers]], coats, sports jackets, skirts, shirts, ties, jeans, shorts, T-shirts, [[polo shirts]], sports shirts, [[tracksuits]], bathing shorts, bathing suits, and bikinis); and undergarments, which include jersey goods and lingerie (e.g. underpants, undershirts, briefs, socks, stockings, and pantyhose).{{Citation needed|date=July 2015}}
==History== The first ready-made garment factory was established in New York in 1831. During the American Civil War the need for ready-made uniforms helped the garment sector grow in the United States.<ref>{{cite book|last1=editor|first1=Eric Arneson,|title=Encyclopedia of U.S. labor and working-class history.|date=2007|publisher=Routledge|location=New York|isbn=9780415968263|page=496|url=https://books.google.com.bd/books?id=zEWsZ81Bd3YC&pg=PA495&dq=%22Ready+Made+Garments%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CD8Q6AEwBzgeahUKEwjD6cquvvDGAhUEupQKHQiRA5M#v=onepage&q=%22Ready%20Made%20Garments%22&f=false|access-date=23 July 2015}}</ref> Near the end of the nineteenth century there were changes in societal views towards ready-made garments: They were no longer seen as only for the lower classes but also for the middle classes. This trend started in the United States. In the beginning they were more popular with men than women.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Aindow|first1=Rosy|title=Dress and identity in British literary culture, 1870-1914|date=2010|publisher=Ashgate|location=Farnham, Surrey|isbn=0754661458|page=37|url=https://books.google.com.bd/books?id=jWVYkHeKQGUC&pg=PA38&dq=%22Ready+Made+Garments%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CDAQ6AEwBWoVChMI0pHRjb7wxgIVhBSUCh0AmAT1#v=onepage&q=%22Ready%20Made%20Garments%22&f=false|access-date=23 July 2015}}</ref> In the late 1860s, twenty-five percent of garments produced in the US were ready-made, but by 1890, the portion had risen to sixty percent. By 1951, ninety percent of garments sold in the United States were ready made. During the same time two-thirds of garments sold in France were ready made.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Green|first1=Nancy L.|title=Ready-to-wear and ready-to-work : a century of industry and immigrants in Paris and New York|date=1997|publisher=Duke University Press.|location=Durham|isbn=0822318741|page=118|url=https://books.google.com.bd/books?id=xNsbnd6XcxMC&pg=PA118&dq=%22Ready+Made+Garments%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CKMBEOgBMBtqFQoTCNKR0Y2-8MYCFYQUlAodAJgE9Q#v=onepage&q=%22Ready%20Made%20Garments%22&f=false|access-date=23 July 2015}}</ref>
