{{Use British English|date=May 2011}}
{{distinguish|text=the fictional setting of two Dr. Seuss children's books, [[Whoville]]}}
The '''Whoniverse''' is the non-narrative name given to the [[fictional universe|fictional setting]] of the television series ''[[Doctor Who]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbcamerica.com/anglophenia/2012/08/doctor-who-science-fact/ |title='Doctor Who' Science Fact: Five Whovian Things That Exist In Real Life |author=Fraser McAlpine |date=2 August 2012 |website=BBC America ‚Äì Anglophenia }}</ref> ''[[Torchwood]]'',<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.doctorwhotv.co.uk/capaldis-past-appearances-not-ignored-53407.htm |title=Capaldi's Past Whoniverse Appearances Not Ignored |date=28 September 2014 |publisher=Doctor Who TV }}</ref> ''[[The Sarah Jane Adventures]]'' and ''[[Class (2016 TV series)|Class]]'' as well as other [[Doctor Who spin-offs|related media]].<ref>Kistler (2013) Page 224</ref><ref name=Databank>Lofficier (1992) [http://www.lofficier.com/dwfrwrd.html Foreword]</ref><ref>{{cite web
|url=http://www.bbcamerica.com/doctor-who/extras/dw50/fun-doctor-personality-quizzes/who-or-what-in-the-whoniverse-would-you-be/ |title=Take the Quiz: Who ‚Äì or What ‚Äì in the Whoniverse Are You? |date= |website=BBC America }}</ref>  The word, a [[portmanteau]] of the words ''Who'' and ''universe'', has also been used to describe the show's production and [[Doctor Who fandom|fanbase]].<ref name=OldMeaning>Haining 1983</ref>

The term is used to link characters, ideas or items which are seen across multiple productions, such as [[Sarah Jane Smith]] from ''Doctor Who'', ''[[K-9 and Company]]'' (1981) and ''The Sarah Jane Adventures'' (2007‚Äì2011),<ref>{{citation |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2008/apr/18/entertainment/et-sarahjane18 |title=She's back in the Whoniverse |date=18 April 2008 |first=Robert |last=Lloyd |publisher=Los Angeles Times }}</ref> [[Jack Harkness]] from ''Doctor Who'' and ''Torchwood'' as well as [[K-9 (Doctor Who)|K-9]] from ''Doctor Who'', ''K-9 and Company'', ''The Sarah Jane Adventures'', and ''[[K-9 (TV series)|K-9]]''.{{citation needed|date=March 2014}}

Unlike the owners of other science fiction franchises, the [[BBC]] takes no position on [[Canon (fiction)|canon]], and recent producers of the show have expressed distaste for the idea.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Davies|first=Russel T.|journal=Doctor Who Magazine|title=Doctor Who Magazine|year=2005|issue=356 |page={{page needed|date=March 2014}}}}</ref>  The term has recently begun to appear in [[mainstream]] press coverage following the popular success of the 2005 ''Doctor Who'' revival.<ref>{{Cite web| url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/jersey/content/articles/2007/07/12/bf07_dalek_cyberman_feature.shtml |first=Ryan| last=Morrison | title=Battle of Flowers: Cybermen and Dalek for Battle| journal=BBC Jersey| issue=| date=12 July 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bleedingcool.com/2013/09/29/peter-capaldis-multiple-appearances-in-the-whoniverse-to-be-explained-by-an-old-russell-t-davies-idea/ |title=Peter Capaldi's Multiple Appearances In The Whoniverse To Be Explained By An Old Russell T Davies Idea |date=29 September 2013 |website=Bleeding Cool }}</ref>

Some have also speculated that the ''[[Blake's 7]]'' series is also part of the same universe, due to a character known as Carnell appearing in the Blake's 7 episode, Weapon, who would also later appear in the Doctor Who novel, ''[[Corpse Marker]]'' and the ''[[Kaldor City]]'' spin-off audio series.

The Whoniverse is also referred to as Earth-5556.

==Features==
The Whoniverse has given rise to a wide variety of lifeforms, including the [[Time Lord]]s,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/doctorwho/classic/episodeguide/timelordorigins.shtml |title=Doctor Who Classic Episode Guide ‚Äì The origins of the Time Lords |date= |website=BBC }} and {{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/doctorwho/s4/features/bulletins/bulletin_time_lords_history |title=Doctor Who ‚Äì A Brief History of Time Lords |date= |website=BBC }}</ref> the [[Dalek]]s,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/doctorwho/classic/episodeguide/dalekhistory1.shtml |title=Doctor Who Classic Episode Guide ‚Äì The first history of the Daleks |date= |website=BBC }} and {{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/doctorwho/classic/episodeguide/dalekhistory2.shtml |title=Doctor Who Classic Episode Guide ‚Äì The second history of the Daleks |date= |website=BBC }}</ref><ref>Kistler (2013) Page 33</ref> and the [[Cyberman|Cybermen]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01rryyj/profiles/cybermen |title=Doctor Who, Series 7 Part 2 ‚Äì Cybermen |date= |website=BBC One }} and {{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/doctorwho/classic/characters/cybermen.shtml |title=Cult Television ‚Äì Doctor Who ‚Äì The Classic Series ‚Äì Characters ‚Äì The Cybermen |date= |website=BBC }}</ref> as well as the [[Sontaran]]s,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0103y2x/profiles/sontarans |title=Doctor Who, Series 6 ‚Äì Sontarans |date= |website=BBC One }}</ref> [[Silurian (Doctor Who)|Silurians]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00rs69w/profiles/silurians |title=Doctor Who, Series 5 ‚Äì Silurians |date= |website=BBC One }}</ref> [[Ice Warrior]]s,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01rryyj/profiles/ice-warriors |title=Doctor Who, Series 7 Part 2 ‚Äì The Ice Warriors |date= |website=BBC One }}</ref> and the [[Weeping Angel]]s, who have appeared in several episodes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p00wqr12/profiles/weeping-angels |title=Doctor Who, Series 7 Part 1 ‚Äì Weeping Angels |date= |website=BBC One }}</ref>

Due to the [[time travel]]ling nature of the show, the Whoniverse setting has been covered across points from its formation in a [[Big Bang|big bang]] event (in 1983's ''[[Terminus (Doctor Who)|Terminus]]'' and the 1985 audio drama ''[[Slipback]]''),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p01l185b |title=Doctor Who, Season 20, Terminus, Part 3, Terminus: Part 3 |date=22 February 2013 |website=BBC One }}</ref> to its [[heat death of the universe|heat death]] in the year "100 trillion" ("[[Utopia (Doctor Who)|Utopia]]" 2007).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b007qltt |title=Doctor Who, Series 3, Utopia |date= |website=BBC One }} and {{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/doctorwho/s4/episodes/S3_11 |title=Doctor Who ‚Äì Utopia ‚Äì Episode Guide |date= |website=BBC }}</ref>  Important events shown include the [[Time War (Doctor Who)|Time War]], the [[History of the Earth|formation of the Earth]]<ref>{{citation |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=330-Zdk5myk |title=Creation of the Earth ‚Äì Doctor Who ‚Äì The Runaway Bride |work=YouTube |publisher=BBC Worldwide }}</ref> and its eventual destruction in the year "5 billion" ("[[The End of the World (Doctor Who)|The End of the World]]" 2005),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0074dmp |title=Doctor Who, Series 1, The End of the World |date= |website=BBC One }}</ref> and the destruction and recreation of the universe ("[[The Pandorica Opens]]"/"[[The Big Bang (Doctor Who)|The Big Bang]]").{{citation needed|date=March 2014}}

==Alternate usage==
{{Main|Doctor Who fandom}}
In his 1983 book ''Doctor Who: A Celebration; Two Decades Through Time and Space'', [[Peter Haining (author)|Peter Haining]] called his final chapter "The Whoniverse".<ref name=OldMeaning/> The section assembled factual information about all the episodes to date, but also gave information about fan clubs and ancillary entertainments related to the programme.  Thus, the term ''Whoniverse'' referred to everything connected with the programme behind-the-scenes.  In this meaning, standing exhibitions, discussions about the filming of episodes and even the [[Doctor Who fandom|fandom itself]] were considered part of the "Whoniverse".  The term ''Whoniverse'' is still used with this definition today,<ref>{{citation |url=https://twitter.com/bbcdoctorwho/status/415942947998167040 |title=A message from Matt Smith: "To the Whoniverse, thanks a million.  You're the best.  I'll miss you.  And I'll miss the madness." |publisher=twitter.com}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/writersroom/posts/the_sarah_jane_adventures/ |work=BBC ‚Äì Blogs ‚Äì Writersroom |title=The Sarah Jane Adventures |publisher=BBC |date=1 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doctorwhosavetheday.com/ |title=Doctor Who ‚Äì #Save The Day |date= |website=BBC }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbcamerica.com/content/23/anglophenia.jsp?bc_id=76 |title=Jessica Simpson to Enter the Whoniverse? |date=7 February 2007 |website=Anglophenia |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070815152915/http://www.bbcamerica.com/content/23/anglophenia.jsp?bc_id=76 |archivedate=15 August 2007 }}</ref> <!-- not clear that this cite does unambiguously support this usage <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbcamerica.com/doctor-who/extras/the-whoniverse/ |title=Your Guide to the Whoniverse |date= |website=BBC America }}</ref> --> including as the name of a ''Doctor Who'' [[Fan convention|convention]] in [[Australia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehubproductions.com/Events/Whoniverse/ |title=Whoniverse |year=2011 |website=The Hub Productions }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://matt-smith.org/2013/12/whoniverse-the-doctor-is-in-australia-2014-convention/ |title=Whoniverse: The Doctor Is In ‚Äì Australia 2014 Convention |date= |website=Magnificent Matt Smith! ‚Äì Your newest online resource to the 11th Doctor Matt Smith! }}</ref>

